<HEADLINE>
<P>
INTERNATIONAL TRAVELOGUE OF CLUB STYLE; 
</P>
<P>
EURO-AMERICAN LOOKS HAUNT TOKYO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BILL HERSEY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TOKYO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The streets of the Roppongi neighborhood stay alive deep into the night. The 
area is home to the Lexington Queen, a favorite hangout for musicians, celebs, 
models and young Japanese. 
</P>
<P>
"The Lex" is a few steps from Roppongi Square Building, a 10-story structure 
that houses eight discos, a jazz club, a restaurant and a game center. 
</P>
<P>
The most popular club in the building is Java Jive, a restaurant-disco that is 
decorated "Jamaica-style" and features a Jamaican band and a deejay playing 
international disco hits. 
</P>
<P>
Buzz, also in the building, is Tokyo's hottest video dance club with a huge 
screen at one end and monitors showing the latest music videos scattered around 
the club. 
</P>
<P>
But most young Japanese, and many foreigners who live in Japan, prefer pubs, 
especially Charleston's and Paradisio, both in the Roppongi area. 
</P>
<P>
The music is pretty much the same as in the States. The Japanese also keep up 
with the latest U.S. dance crazes. BILL HERSEY 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, The style in Toyko is a hybrid of Euro and Yank club gear. At Buzz, 
Daini, left, in white jodhpurs and stripes, and Masami, right, in black leather 
and distressed denim. Mariko, inset, in animal-print jacket. BILL HERSEY 
</P>
