<HEADLINE>
<P>
BUSH DECLARES ALABAMA FLOODING A DISASTER; ACT PAVES WAY FOR AID 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Bush has declared a disaster in the state of Alabama and ordered 
federal recovery aid because of damage caused by severe storms and flooding. 
</P>
<P>
Bush's order makes funding available to supplement the needs of affected 
individuals and local governments in Coffee County. 
</P>
<P>
The assistance will be coordinated by the Federal Emergency Management Agency 
and can include temporary housing, grants, low-interest loans to cover 
uninsured property losses and other programs to help residents and businesses 
recover. 
</P>
<P>
FEMA, meanwhile, is conducting damage surveys in other areas and additional 
counties may be designated for assistance when the assessments are completed. 
</P>
<P>
The storms and flooding struck the southeastern part of the state beginning 
March 15. 
</P>
<P>
Elba, Ala., in Coffee County, was inundated Saturday when a levee along the Pea 
River burst after the region was pummeled with up to 16 inches of rain. Across 
the South, the flooding forced hundreds to be evacuated and was blamed for at 
least 11 deaths. 
</P>
<P>
Rescuers on Thursday found two missing servicemen along the Pea, where the pair 
had launched a canoe Wednesday to view flood damage. The search continued to 
the northeast in Dale County for a third soldier missing for four days. All 
three were based at Ft. Rucker, Ala., the U.S. Army's main flight training 
base. 
</P>
<P>
Rivers in Alabama continued to recede Thursday, but towns on the Florida 
Panhandle and in southern Georgia prepared for the bulge of water from last 
weekend's storms working its way downstream. 
</P>
<P>
In Florida, flooding along several rivers across the Panhandle caused about 
2,500 residents along the lower Choctawhatchee to flee. 
</P>
<P>
In Georgia, forecasters predicted that the Ocmulgee River would crest at seven 
feet above flood stage today in Hawkinsville. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, After ImmersionPresident Bush declared a major disaster in the state of 
Alabama, ordering federal recovery aid for damage caused by a week of severe 
storms and flooding. Across the South, the flooding forced hundreds of 
evacuations and at least 11 deaths. In the Alabama town of Elba, which was 
especially hard hit after a levee broke, citizens were beginning the cleanup. 
At the Church of God -- which was inundated over the weekend -- all the pews 
were placed outside to dry, left. Associated Press 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
