<HEADLINE>
<P>
HER EXPERIENCE WITH A STEPMOTHER IS NOTHING LIKE CINDERELLA'S 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By HEIDI BERNADETTE MACK, THE CHRISTIAN SCIENCE MONITOR 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Not all stepfamilies have to struggle as they work toward love and unity. My 
own experience was happy from the beginning. 
</P>
<P>
I'm sure that my natural mother loved me, and I her, even though I don't 
remember her very well. I was 8 and my sister 12 when our mother died. 
</P>
<P>
But we didn't have the mother-daughter closeness apparent in some families. I 
don't remember listening to bedtime stories while being tucked gently beneath 
the covers or while cuddling on her lap, her cool hands stroking my hair. 
</P>
<P>
When my father announced his plans to remarry a number of months later, I was 
surprised but not unhappy. 
</P>
<P>
I still remember where we were and where we had eaten dinner, how the 
gold-flecked diamonds on the seats of my dad's truck felt under my hand as he 
told us. 
</P>
<P>
Not having spent much time with my natural mother, I was ready to welcome a new 
mother who would be home when I went to bed at night and got up in the morning. 
</P>
<P>
I don't remember too much from the first few months in our revised family. Some 
things do stand out -- getting over the awkwardness of calling a new woman 
"Mom," the Madame Alexander doll with her yellow dotted dress she brought me, 
and adjusting to a new schedule that, for the first time, included regular 
bedtime hours and church. 
</P>
<P>
And all the new rules! 
</P>
<P>
Having been used to spending a lot of time on our own, my sister and I weren't 
used to someone's telling us what to wear, what we could watch on TV and what 
to eat. 
</P>
<P>
No more mornings of Pop Tarts and Cap'n Crunch. We were now awakened to a 
mother who served us oatmeal and wheat toast. The days of wearing shorts and 
flip-flops to school were definitely over. Mom made me some outfits that I 
hated to wear, and I didn't tell her because I didn't want to hurt her 
feelings. They were so out of style! Especially the green pantsuit with the 
gold trim! Junior high, as we all know, is a place where you have to conform or 
die of embarrassment. 
</P>
<P>
All in all, though, changing a few habits and styles wasn't too much to ask of 
us, and it didn't take me long to adjust to having a new mother. 
</P>
<P>
I'll never forget the time we were making chocolate chip cookies late one 
Saturday morning. In my eagerness to taste the batter, I leaned over just a 
little too far and got my hair tangled in the beaters. 
</P>
<P>
She and sister were sure it was the funniest thing they'd ever seen. They made 
me stand, glaring, for a picture with my gooey hair twisted around the beater. 
</P>
<P>
And the time our dog, Nemo, was killed by a car during a lightning storm. When 
I came home from school, Mom pulled me onto her lap to comfort me. I was crying 
uncontrollably. She was completely at a loss. 
</P>
<P>
"I'll do anything, anything, if you'll just stop crying," she said. 
</P>
<P>
"Don't . . . ," I sobbed, stuttering, "make me wear . . . that green pantsuit 
anymore. . . ." 
</P>
<P>
Poor Nemo was temporarily forgotten. How we laugh about that now! 
</P>
<P>
My sister had a tougher time adjusting than I did, but not really because of 
the stepmother situation. It was just that hard time of maturing, leaving 
childhood behind for the new challenges of being a teen-ager. 
</P>
<P>
Looking back, not only did we gain a new mother, we also got a new sister 
(already married by that time) and lots of other wonderful new relatives. 
</P>
<P>
I cherish this new family situation. It seems foreign to think of my mother and 
sister as stepmother and stepsister. They're simply family. 
</P>
<P>
It was wonderful, and still is, to have a mother who cared for me as for her 
own. What makes a family, after all, is not merely blood ties. 
</P>
<P>
To me, a real mother is the woman who brings a child up with care, love and 
respect -- regardless of whether she brought him or her into the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
