</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
TAXABLE SALES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Clipboard researched by Kathie Bozanich and Janice L. Jones / Los Angeles 
Times; Graphics by Doris Shields / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Municipal merchants ran up $5.8 billion in taxable sales during the second 
quarter of 1989, the most recent period for which information is available. 
That was a 10% increase from the second quarter of 1988, with the biggest jump, 
30%, occurring in San Juan Capistrano. Three cities suffered dips from 1988 -- 
the largest being 8% in Placentia. The $799.5 million spent in Anaheim was the 
largest amount in any one city, 14% of the total. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
