<DATELINE>
<P>
TAMPA, Fla. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Batman" and "Beetlejuice" director Tim Burton is being deliberately vague 
about his latest project -- "Edward Scissorhands," a suburban fantasy film 
about a man created with shears of metal for fingers. 
</P>
<P>
"It's very different," Burton said. 
</P>
<P>
"We're going to sort of make it up as we go along." 
</P>
<P>
Burton and stars Johnny Depp, Dianne Wiest and Winona Ryder arrived here 
Thursday to start three months of production on the film, scheduled for 
Christmas release. 
</P>
<P>
According to 20th Century Fox, "Scissorhands" is about a man who was created, 
not born. He was given everything he needed to lead a full life, except one 
thing: His inventor's untimely death left Edward with sharp shears of metal 
where his fingers should have been. 
</P>
<P>
He lives in seclusion until he is discovered by an earnest Avon lady and his 
life changes forever. 
</P>
<P>
Preparations for filming have been made in a Tampa neighborhood, where several 
homes have been painted garish colors to create a surreal suburban atmosphere. 
</P>
